62 SECTION 6.
63 Said article is further amended by revising Code Section 40-14-7, relating to visibility of
64 vehicle from which device is operated, as follows:
65 "40-14-7.
66 Except as provided for in Code Section 40-14-18, no No stationary speed detection device
67 shall be employed by county, municipal, college, or university law enforcement officers
68 where the vehicle from which the such device is operated is obstructed from the view of
69 approaching motorists or is otherwise not visible for a distance of at least 500 feet."
70 SECTION 7.
71 Said article is further amended in Code Section 40-14-11, relating to investigations by
72 commissioner of public safety, issuance of order suspending or revoking permit, and ratio
73 of speeding fines to agency's budget, by revising subsection (d) as follows:
74 "(d) There shall be a rebuttable presumption that a law enforcement agency is employing
75 speed detection devices for purposes other than the promotion of the public health, welfare,
76 and safety if the fines levied based on the use of speed detection devices for speeding
77 offenses are equal to or greater than 35 percent of a municipal or county law enforcement
78 agency's budget. For purposes of this Code section, fines collected for citations issued for
79 violations of Code Section 40-6-180 shall be included when calculating total speeding fine
80 revenue for the agency; provided, however, that fines for speeding violations exceeding 20
81 miles per hour over the established speed limit and civil monetary penalties for speeding
82 violations issued pursuant to Code Section 40-14-18 shall not be considered when
83 calculating total speeding fine revenue for the such agency."
